Interesting, looks like information about comment style is ignored during parsing:

```java
public class Comment extends ASTNode {
        public final static int TYPE_SINGLE_LINE = 0;
	public final static int TYPE_MULTILINE = 1;
	public final static int TYPE_PHPDOC = 2;
        // ...
}
```

In plugins/org.eclipse.php.formatter.core/src/org/eclipse/php/formatter/core/CodeFormatterVisitor.java, around [line 1224](https://github.com/eclipse/pdt/blob/c3072f7436947ef8f2108331e26e711135300753/plugins/org.eclipse.php.formatter.core/src/org/eclipse/php/formatter/core/CodeFormatterVisitor.java#L1224):
```java
	int commentTokLen = commentContent.startsWith("#") ? 1 : 2;//$NON-NLS-1$
	commentWords = Arrays.asList(
			MagicMemberUtil.WHITESPACE_SEPERATOR.split(commentContent.substring(commentTokLen).trim()));
	commentWords = removeEmptyString(commentWords);
	commentContent = join(commentWords, " "); //$NON-NLS-1$
	commentContent = commentContent.trim();

	boolean newLineStart = true;
	appendToBuffer("//"); //$NON-NLS-1$

	for (String word : commentWords) {
		if (this.preferences.comment_line_length != 9999 && !newLineStart
				&& (lineWidth + 1 + word.length() > this.preferences.comment_line_length)) {
			insertNewLine();
			// start at first column, and more than
			// comment_line_length
			if (!startAtFirstColumn || (startAtFirstColumn && doIndentForComment)) {
				indentForComment(indentationLevelDescending);
			}
			appendToBuffer("//"); //$NON-NLS-1$
			insertSpaces(1);
			appendToBuffer(word);
		} else {
			insertSpaces(1);
			appendToBuffer(word);
			newLineStart = false;
		}
	}
```

The token length is obtained for parsing purposes, but when the formatting takes place, it just appends // to the buffer without consideration for the comment style.

**Describe the bug**
PDT code assist features do not properly handle child classes.

**Describe the eclipse environment**
Eclipse PDT 2020-03

**Describe your system**
Windows 10
PHP 7.4.6

**To Reproduce**
Enter the following into a PHP editor. Note that code completions, mouse over floating windows etcetera, for $this->one inside the ModTwo class constructor show $this->one as a One class instead of the expected ModOne class.

```php
<?php

class One
{
    /**
     * One
     *
     * @var string
     */
    public string $one;
}

class ModOne extends One
{
    /**
     * ModOne
     *
     * @var string
     */
    public string $modone;
}

class Two
{
    /**
     * One class
     *
     * @var One
     */
    public One $one;

    public function __construct() {
        $this->one = new One();
    }
}

class ModTwo extends Two
{
    public function __construct() {
        //$this->one still seen as a One class by IDE when it should be seen as
        //a ModOne class. The type hint does not help.
        /* @var ModOne $this->one */
        $this->one = new ModOne();
    }
}

$x = new ModTwo();
var_dump($x->one); //Outputs correct ModOne object
```

**Steps to reproduce the behavior**
See previous section.

**Expected behavior**
1. PDT should treat the $this->one property inside the ModTwo class constructor as a ModOne class, not its parent One class.
2. If a type hint conflicts with what PDT thinks a variable is, the type hint should take precedence, which is why the type hint was added.

